{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1827879e-948d-4dcb-a288-821a30c8b286","content":"Here's a quick reference:\n\n| Framework | Attribute | Example |\n|-----------|-----------|---------|\n| **MSTest** | `[Ignore(\"reason\")]` | `[Ignore(\"Blocked by #123\")]` |\n| **xUnit** | `[Fact(Skip = \"reason\")]` | `[Fact(Skip = \"Blocked by #123\")]` |\n| **NUnit** | `[Ignore(\"reason\")]` | `[Ignore(\"Blocked by #123\")]` |\n| **TUnit** | `[Skip(\"reason\")]` | `[Skip(\"Blocked by #123\")]` |\n\n**Notes:**\n- For xUnit `[Theory]` tests, use `[Theory(Skip = \"reason\")]`.\n- MSTest and NUnit both use `[Ignore]` but from different namespaces (`Microsoft.VisualStudio.TestTools.UnitTesting` vs `NUnit.Framework`).\n- All four frameworks will report skipped tests in `dotnet test` output so they stay visible.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3747c9b0-a9fa-40b5-b8a9-fc7ae24e04ce","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about test skip/ignore attributes across four .NET test frameworks. This is a knowledge question - no tools needed.","outputTokens":284,"requestId":"BD08:2F6EDC:1E8E1D2:223BCF0:6A07C4BD"},"id":"41e55ca7-5746-4895-989e-f607a4993736","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:13:40.728Z","parentId":"65fb7a2a-f9a7-412b-b047-a1cefecdb4af"}
